1
00:00:15,440 --> 00:00:17,024
[DOOR SQUEAKS]

2
00:00:17,025 --> 00:00:18,614
[FOOTSTEPS ECHOING]

3
00:00:29,079 --> 00:00:31,078
[PHONE RINGING]

4
00:00:36,294 --> 00:00:39,171
[GIGGLING]

5
00:00:39,172 --> 00:00:41,890
[PIANO PLAYS]

6
00:00:51,977 --> 00:00:53,811
[DOOR CLOSES]

7
00:00:53,812 --> 00:00:57,351
[FLUTE PLAYS]

8
00:00:59,067 --> 00:01:03,017
[FOOTSTEPS ECHOING]

9
00:01:03,613 --> 00:01:07,305
[CARS HONKING]

10
00:01:16,585 --> 00:01:20,963
BOY: I worry maybe people aren't
gonna like me when I go to a party.

11
00:01:20,964 --> 00:01:23,784
Isn't that crazy?

12
00:01:24,134 --> 00:01:29,634
Do you ever get kind of a sick feeling in
your stomach when you dread things?

13
00:01:29,973 --> 00:01:33,475
I wouldn't wanna miss a party,
but every time I go to one...

14
00:01:33,476 --> 00:01:37,479
...I keep feeling like
the whole world's against me.

15
00:01:37,480 --> 00:01:40,983
See, I've spent my whole life
in military academies.

16
00:01:40,984 --> 00:01:44,111
My mother doesn't have a place for me
where she lives...

17
00:01:44,112 --> 00:01:46,822
...and she doesn't know
what else to do with me.

18
00:01:46,823 --> 00:01:51,744
You mustn't misunderstand about
my mother. She's really a lovely person.

19
00:01:51,745 --> 00:01:56,498
I guess every boy thinks his mother
is beautiful, but my mother really is.

20
00:01:56,499 --> 00:02:01,295
She tells me in every letter how sorry
she is that we're not together more...

21
00:02:01,296 --> 00:02:04,673
...but she has to think of her work.

22
00:02:04,674 --> 00:02:08,802
One time we were together, though.
She met me in San Francisco once...

23
00:02:08,803 --> 00:02:13,849
...and we were together for two whole
days, just like we were sweethearts.

24
00:02:13,850 --> 00:02:17,853
It was the most wonderful time
I ever had.

25
00:02:17,854 --> 00:02:22,524
Then I had to go back
to the military academy.

26
00:02:22,525 --> 00:02:27,860
Every time I walk into that barracks,
I get a kind of...

27
00:02:32,953 --> 00:02:35,722
A kind of a...

28
00:02:39,834 --> 00:02:42,141
I'm sorry.

29
00:02:48,843 --> 00:02:51,887
Kind of a depressed feeling.

30
00:02:51,888 --> 00:02:56,392
It's got hard, stone walls.
You know what I mean?

31
00:02:56,393 --> 00:03:00,906
I guess I've bored you enough,
telling you about myself.

32
00:03:01,564 --> 00:03:03,399
Thank you.

33
00:03:03,400 --> 00:03:08,028
Sorry about that. I goofed up the last
couple of lines. I guess I'm nervous.

34
00:03:08,029 --> 00:03:10,336
That's okay. You did very well.

35
00:03:22,544 --> 00:03:24,800
I'm sorry.

36
00:03:25,380 --> 00:03:28,200
[VIOLIN PLAYS]

37
00:03:49,446 --> 00:03:52,364
Thank you. You play very well.

38
00:03:52,365 --> 00:03:57,865
Now Mrs. Tossoff's gonna play notes
for you. Sing them back to us. Like so:

39
00:03:59,539 --> 00:04:01,665
<i>La, la, la, la, la, la, la</i>

40
00:04:01,666 --> 00:04:06,378
- It's too low for me.
- You're a tenor? You want to start here?

41
00:04:06,379 --> 00:04:08,797
<i>La, la, la, la, la, la, la</i>

42
00:04:08,798 --> 00:04:11,670
Louder, please.

43
00:04:31,821 --> 00:04:34,693
[CHATTERING]

44
00:04:49,172 --> 00:04:51,256
I'm so nervous.

45
00:04:51,257 --> 00:04:53,801
- I'm not singing.
- But you have to.

46
00:04:53,802 --> 00:04:56,261
- But I came to dance.
- You have to sing too.

47
00:04:56,262 --> 00:04:58,847
- And act, and play an instrument.
- All three?

48
00:04:58,848 --> 00:05:02,142
GIRL: it says "performing arts."
- You don't have to do everything.

49
00:05:02,143 --> 00:05:07,643
- Sure as shit helps, baby.
- Thank you. Next group, please. Hurry.

50
00:05:08,191 --> 00:05:11,485
LISA: Oh, I like your nose ring.
- I'm into culture.

51
00:05:11,486 --> 00:05:15,781
- Does that hurt, or is that ethnic?
BERG: Music, please, Mrs. Snell.

52
00:05:15,782 --> 00:05:20,449
Please pay attention.
We have a lot to do today.

53
00:05:22,580 --> 00:05:25,749
- I hate my legs.
GIRL: Yeah. Me too.

54
00:05:25,750 --> 00:05:30,087
- I've tried every diet in the whole world.
- Really? Me too.

55
00:05:30,088 --> 00:05:34,883
But you can't help your glands.
I'm sorry! I'm just so nervous.

56
00:05:34,884 --> 00:05:38,680
Relax! Come on, use your body.

57
00:05:45,854 --> 00:05:47,604
[HONKING]

58
00:05:47,605 --> 00:05:51,525
- Careful. That's 7000 worth of machine.
DRIVER: Dollars or pounds?

59
00:05:51,526 --> 00:05:53,485
- Don't touch the rotary pots.
- What pots?

60
00:05:53,486 --> 00:05:55,237
BRUNO:
I got it set on sawtooth.

61
00:05:55,238 --> 00:06:00,033
Why can't he play piccolo? Something
sensible. Or the accordion, like Papa did.

62
00:06:00,034 --> 00:06:03,912
Same reason you drive a checker and
not a Roman chariot. It's progress.

63
00:06:03,913 --> 00:06:08,940
My son's head is into the future.
And Papa could never play the accordion.

64
00:06:13,256 --> 00:06:17,092
- Do you think you're talented?
- You swine! You coward! You cad!

65
00:06:17,093 --> 00:06:19,761
You dare judge me in my misfortitude?

66
00:06:19,762 --> 00:06:23,724
You dare to ask me the question
who is the father of my child?

67
00:06:23,725 --> 00:06:28,645
- You! You! I point to you, Nigel!
MAN: Next, please.

68
00:06:28,646 --> 00:06:34,146
The next group of musicians can
go to the fifth floor now, please.

69
00:06:47,332 --> 00:06:49,333
- Name?
- Excuse me, miss.

70
00:06:49,334 --> 00:06:53,295
You don't need his name. He's not here
for the audition. He's my partner.

71
00:06:53,296 --> 00:06:55,631
- What school's he from?
- He ain't into school.

72
00:06:55,632 --> 00:07:00,886
He's just helping me out with my
dancing. But it's me who's auditioning.

73
00:07:00,887 --> 00:07:04,890
Mulholland, Shirley. I'm all fixed up.
I filled in all your papers and all.

74
00:07:04,891 --> 00:07:07,476
He doesn't go upstairs
without filling in his name.

75
00:07:07,477 --> 00:07:12,814
Leroy's his name, but I'm auditioning.
Shirley Mulholland. That's two L's.

76
00:07:12,815 --> 00:07:17,611
- And don't ask him to do no writing.
- Doesn't he talk, even?

77
00:07:17,612 --> 00:07:20,822
He ain't into conversation
until you get to know him.

78
00:07:20,823 --> 00:07:25,410
- Leroy what?
- Leroy Johnson. Can we go up now?

79
00:07:25,411 --> 00:07:28,372
He's not going up
until he checks his knife.

80
00:07:28,373 --> 00:07:31,833
We ain't staying long enough for
no trouble. He's just helping a friend.

81
00:07:31,834 --> 00:07:35,337
He's not helping out anyone
unless he checks his knife.

82
00:07:35,338 --> 00:07:39,851
This is the High School for Performing
Arts. We don't cut each other up here.

83
00:07:40,051 --> 00:07:42,177
- You want it?
- I want it.

84
00:07:42,178 --> 00:07:45,152
- You sure you want it?
- Yeah, I'm sure.

85
00:07:45,848 --> 00:07:49,644
- Promise you won't steal it, now?
- I promise.

86
00:07:51,396 --> 00:07:54,022
SHIRLEY: Thanks, ma'am.
SHERWOOD: Name?

87
00:07:54,023 --> 00:07:58,228
Don't worry, baby. I got lots of knives.

88
00:07:58,319 --> 00:08:01,571
TEACHER: What are you going to do?
- I was gonna sing.

89
00:08:01,572 --> 00:08:05,117
- You don't have to sing, honey.
- We know our rights.

90
00:08:05,118 --> 00:08:09,496
- You can't refuse her an audition.
- She's not supposed to sing her audition.

91
00:08:09,497 --> 00:08:14,710
Please, excuse me, if you don't mind.
Honey, you don't have to sing for us...

92
00:08:14,711 --> 00:08:18,797
- ...because this is the drama department.
- When she sings, it is drama.

93
00:08:18,798 --> 00:08:21,978
- What's your name, honey?
FINSECKER: Finsecker.

94
00:08:23,886 --> 00:08:25,470
Doris Finsecker.

95
00:08:25,471 --> 00:08:29,113
[WHISTLING]

96
00:08:31,227 --> 00:08:34,438
- Hi.
- How do you do?

97
00:08:34,439 --> 00:08:36,898
- What's your name?
- Ralph Garci.

98
00:08:36,899 --> 00:08:41,236
- Who was your teacher?
- Well, my father taught me.

99
00:08:41,237 --> 00:08:46,241
He's doing work for the government.
I'm not supposed to talk about it...

100
00:08:46,242 --> 00:08:51,742
...but my father played some of the
most beautiful symphonies...

101
00:08:52,665 --> 00:08:55,998
- ...in the whole world once.
- What did he play?

102
00:08:56,586 --> 00:08:58,996
Trombones.

103
00:08:59,547 --> 00:09:02,469
And French horns.

104
00:09:03,468 --> 00:09:04,748
English horns.

105
00:09:06,596 --> 00:09:08,889
- Saxophones.
- Anything else?

106
00:09:08,890 --> 00:09:10,530
Yeah.

107
00:09:11,642 --> 00:09:17,142
- Bongos, maracas, that sort of stuff.
- What did he teach you?

108
00:09:24,947 --> 00:09:27,115
Why don't you
try the dance department?

109
00:09:27,116 --> 00:09:31,036
- Why do you want to go to school here?
- Should I tell him?

110
00:09:31,037 --> 00:09:32,523
Yeah, tell him.

111
00:09:33,039 --> 00:09:36,783
We can't afford a professional
children's school.

112
00:09:38,044 --> 00:09:43,173
Okay. if you want to sing, go ahead.
Then we'll look at your acting.

113
00:09:43,424 --> 00:09:45,342
I'm a little nervous.

114
00:09:45,343 --> 00:09:50,389
Don't be shy, Sheila. Come over here.
What are you going to do?

115
00:09:50,390 --> 00:09:54,082
- I'm doing The Towering Inferno.
- What?

116
00:09:54,644 --> 00:09:58,271
- You know, the movie?
- Oh.

117
00:09:58,272 --> 00:10:01,608
All right, I'm playing O.J. Simpson.
I'm in this building.

118
00:10:01,609 --> 00:10:05,445
There's fire all around, right?
So I go to the elevator.

119
00:10:05,446 --> 00:10:08,115
- Think of it as a concentration exercise.
- Concentrate.

120
00:10:08,116 --> 00:10:09,658
TEACHER:
Just sing to Michael...

121
00:10:09,659 --> 00:10:15,159
- ...and don't worry about anybody else.
- I don't think I can. I can't just stare.

122
00:10:15,331 --> 00:10:17,331
TEACHER:
He won't mind.

123
00:10:20,378 --> 00:10:25,661
- Waiting for the elevator.
FINSECKER: Press the button, Doris.

124
00:10:26,008 --> 00:10:29,678
[PIANO PLAYS]

125
00:10:29,679 --> 00:10:31,217
Her brother Harvey.

126
00:10:39,188 --> 00:10:42,149
[SINGING] <i>Memories</i>

127
00:10:42,150 --> 00:10:47,650
<i>Like the corners of my mind</i>

128
00:10:47,697 --> 00:10:52,534
<i>Misty water-colored memories</i>

129
00:10:52,535 --> 00:10:54,202
Doesn't come, so now I'm getting mad.

130
00:10:54,203 --> 00:10:57,177
DORIS:
<i>Of the way we were</i>

131
00:11:00,084 --> 00:11:03,315
<i>Scattered pictures</i>

132
00:11:03,504 --> 00:11:08,884
<i>Of the smiles we left behind</i>

133
00:11:08,885 --> 00:11:14,264
<i>Smiles we gave to one another</i>

134
00:11:14,265 --> 00:11:17,476
<i>Of the way we were</i>

135
00:11:17,477 --> 00:11:20,553
[SIGHS]

136
00:11:21,439 --> 00:11:25,696
<i>Can it be that it was all so simple then?</i>

137
00:11:26,736 --> 00:11:30,171
<i>Or has time rewritten every line?</i>

138
00:11:31,908 --> 00:11:35,600
<i>If we had the chance to do it all again</i>

139
00:11:35,870 --> 00:11:40,540
Finally it comes, so I get in.
Okay, and there's people all around.

140
00:11:40,541 --> 00:11:43,669
And they're looking right at me.

141
00:11:43,920 --> 00:11:46,176
<i>Memories</i>

142
00:11:46,589 --> 00:11:50,589
<i>May be beautiful and yet</i>

143
00:11:51,719 --> 00:11:55,411
<i>What's too painful to remember</i>

144
00:11:56,432 --> 00:11:59,919
<i>We simply choose to forget</i>

145
00:12:02,146 --> 00:12:04,966
<i>So it's the laughter</i>

146
00:12:06,609 --> 00:12:08,968
<i>We will remember</i>

147
00:12:11,280 --> 00:12:14,357
<i>Whenever we remember</i>

148
00:12:16,410 --> 00:12:21,910
<i>The way we were</i>

149
00:12:29,590 --> 00:12:33,760
Yeah, my father taught me. I'm not
supposed to talk about him right now.

150
00:12:33,761 --> 00:12:36,721
He's doing a little bit of work
for the government, but...

151
00:12:36,722 --> 00:12:41,476
My father is very, very famous.
He danced with the Rockettes.

152
00:12:41,477 --> 00:12:44,042
Sure. Would you begin, please?

153
00:12:45,106 --> 00:12:48,233
- I'll be doing "Swanee River" for you.
- Okay.

154
00:12:48,234 --> 00:12:50,986
RALPH:
And...

155
00:12:50,987 --> 00:12:56,487
Hon? "Swanee River," please.
Hit it.

156
00:13:00,162 --> 00:13:04,499
Doris, what would you do
if you don't make it?

157
00:13:04,500 --> 00:13:05,833
We'll make it.

158
00:13:06,168 --> 00:13:08,835
MAN:
Next, please.

159
00:13:08,838 --> 00:13:11,923
But I that am not shaped
for sportive tricks...

160
00:13:11,924 --> 00:13:15,010
...nor made to court
an amorous looking glass...

161
00:13:15,011 --> 00:13:18,908
...I that am... Cheated of...
Oh, I'm sorry.

162
00:13:34,655 --> 00:13:37,073
Why don't you try
the drama department?

163
00:13:37,074 --> 00:13:42,537
If again "it was not well cut,"
he'd answer, I spake not true:

164
00:13:42,538 --> 00:13:45,206
This is called the Reply Churlish.

165
00:13:45,207 --> 00:13:48,376
Nobody talks about it,
but there's a quota system.

166
00:13:48,377 --> 00:13:53,465
Your chances are better if you're black,
Puerto Rican or everything, like me.

167
00:13:53,466 --> 00:13:57,927
- I am Puerto Rican.
- Not on your paper you ain't, Garci.

168
00:13:57,928 --> 00:14:02,015
- Your daddy doing government work.
- That's the truth.

169
00:14:02,016 --> 00:14:06,895
And he left you his tap shoes, right?
Does he work for Pepsi-Cola too?

170
00:14:06,896 --> 00:14:08,228
BRUNO:
Be careful.

171
00:14:08,230 --> 00:14:11,066
- To the left. Left.
MARTELLI: Come the other way.

172
00:14:11,067 --> 00:14:12,901
All right.

173
00:14:12,902 --> 00:14:16,132
Easy, now. Straight back, Bruno?

174
00:14:17,365 --> 00:14:21,057
- Where do you want this at?
BRUNO: Far corner.

175
00:14:22,286 --> 00:14:24,913
How do you do?

176
00:14:24,914 --> 00:14:26,915
BRUNO:
Okay. Fine.

177
00:14:26,916 --> 00:14:31,336
Great. Look, I'll do that. You just go
and get the rest of the stuff, okay?

178
00:14:31,337 --> 00:14:33,755
Oh, Martelli. Bruno Martelli.

179
00:14:33,756 --> 00:14:37,342
Would you like to set up
your equipment, Mr. Martelli?

180
00:14:37,343 --> 00:14:39,958
[SLAPPING]

181
00:14:42,431 --> 00:14:44,182
TEACHER:
Who taught you?

182
00:14:44,183 --> 00:14:49,683
Who taught me? My father taught me.
He's in Spain. He makes Westerns.

183
00:14:50,106 --> 00:14:54,693
- Why do you want to go to school here?
- Because Freddie went here.

184
00:14:54,694 --> 00:14:58,822
- Freddie?
- Freddie Prinze. He's the best.

185
00:14:58,823 --> 00:15:02,742
- So you want to be an actor, huh?
- Yeah, sure, I want to be an actor.

186
00:15:02,743 --> 00:15:05,453
Judy, Judy, Judy.
Top of the world, Ma.

187
00:15:05,454 --> 00:15:10,458
We don't want you to perform. We want
to see who you are. You understand?

188
00:15:10,459 --> 00:15:13,086
- Right.
- Use your own experience.

189
00:15:13,087 --> 00:15:16,673
Be simple, be honest,
but most of all, be yourself.

190
00:15:16,674 --> 00:15:21,494
- Be honest. Be simple. Be yourself?
- Be yourself.

191
00:15:22,096 --> 00:15:27,058
I'm God, see? And God
is Puerto Rican, you got that? Now.

192
00:15:27,059 --> 00:15:31,396
God works in a casa de steam,
you know. It's a steam bath, right?

193
00:15:31,397 --> 00:15:36,897
And he's talking to this angel. This angel
is a computer. An electronic computer.

194
00:15:37,695 --> 00:15:42,741
I'm God, see? That's why I'm standing
on this chair, you got that? Good.

195
00:15:42,742 --> 00:15:45,254
[PIANO PLAYS]

196
00:15:52,001 --> 00:15:56,308
Does he wanna be a musician
or an airline pilot?

197
00:15:56,589 --> 00:16:00,717
Mr. Martelli. We are ready when you are.
Would you care to begin?

198
00:16:00,718 --> 00:16:03,948
BRUNO:
Oh, okay. Sure.

199
00:16:28,329 --> 00:16:33,829
Mr. Martelli.

200
00:16:37,880 --> 00:16:39,315
Mr. Martelli!

201
00:16:41,050 --> 00:16:44,928
Thank you. One instrument
at a time will be quite sufficient.

202
00:16:44,929 --> 00:16:48,056
I could do it in 4/4
if you prefer a disco beat.

203
00:16:48,057 --> 00:16:51,185
[DISCO MUSIC PLAYS]

204
00:18:16,478 --> 00:18:19,761
She's a disaster.

205
00:18:22,318 --> 00:18:27,818
Romeo, wherefore art thou Romeo?
Deny thy father and refuse thy name.

206
00:18:28,282 --> 00:18:31,326
Or, if thou wilt not,
be but sworn my love...

207
00:18:31,327 --> 00:18:36,331
...and then I'll no longer be a Capu...
Capu... Capu-something.

208
00:18:36,332 --> 00:18:40,752
TEACHER: Capulet.
- Like Cappelletti, the football player?

209
00:18:40,753 --> 00:18:43,420
- Something like that.
- That's what I mean.

210
00:18:47,301 --> 00:18:50,553
- Where's his application?
- He doesn't have one.

211
00:18:50,554 --> 00:18:53,272
Well, get him one.

212
00:19:10,908 --> 00:19:14,549
- What do you call that?
- Wicked.

213
00:19:26,548 --> 00:19:28,174
Thou art thyself.

214
00:19:28,175 --> 00:19:31,552
Thou art not a Montagoo...
Montagazz... Who knows?

215
00:19:31,553 --> 00:19:37,053
This is the last day of auditions. We've
seen a lot of students. We're punchy.

216
00:19:37,518 --> 00:19:39,477
- We're gonna take a break.
- Ah, yeah.

217
00:19:39,478 --> 00:19:43,189
Go next door to Mrs. Shime.
Have her audition you.

218
00:19:43,190 --> 00:19:46,484
TEACHER: Right next door.
- I tell her that you sent me?

219
00:19:46,485 --> 00:19:48,569
TEACHER: Yeah.
- All right.

220
00:19:48,570 --> 00:19:50,154
By the way...

221
00:19:50,155 --> 00:19:55,284
- ...you were reading the girl's part.
- Shit.

222
00:19:55,452 --> 00:19:59,580
SHIRLEY: You're not into high school.
LEROY: I'm into dancing.

223
00:19:59,581 --> 00:20:02,625
You're into ass, you mean. You don't
have to go to high school for that.

224
